cess\",\n1896:    \"status\": \"success\",\n1950:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2015:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n2059:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: com.mchange:mchange-commons-java:0.2.15\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe generated native test suite failed only in `PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest`:\\n\\n- `propertyBoundTextFieldSyncsFromTheBean()`\\n- `propertyBoundTextFieldWritesUserChangesBackToTheBean()`\\n\\nBoth failures came from Swing/AWT X11 toolkit initialization inside the native image, not from missing `com.mchange` library metadata.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### `propertyBoundTextFieldSyncsFromTheBean()`\\nThis failed with `java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: sun/awt/X11/XErrorHandlerUtil` while `java.desktop` was initializing `sun.awt.X11GraphicsEnvironment` and `sun.awt.X11.XToolkit`.\\n\\nRoot cause: the generated test constructs `PropertyBoundTextField` and uses `SwingUtilities`, which forces native-image execution down the Linux X11 AWT/Swing path. That path depends on JDK-internal `sun.awt.X11.*` classes and platform GUI initialization. This is a native-image/X11 platform issue, not missing reachability metadata for `com.mchange:mchange-commons-java`.\\n\\n### `propertyBoundTextFieldWritesUserChangesBackToTheBean()`\\nThis failed with `java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: Could not initialize class sun.awt.X11.XToolkit` when checking or entering the EDT.\\n\\nRoot cause: same as above. The first X11 toolkit initialization failure poisoned subsequent Swing access, so the second test failed immediately when `SwingUtilities` touched the toolkit.\\n\\n## Codex log assessment\\n\\nThe Codex metadata-fix log shows it kept chasing JDK Swing/AWT internals for this GUI path, adding metadata for classes such as `java.awt.GraphicsEnvironment` and `sun.awt.SunToolkit`, but the final Gradle failure still ended in X11 toolkit initialization errors (`sun.awt.X11.XErrorHandlerUtil` / `sun.awt.X11.XToolkit`).\\n\\nThat indicates the remaining problem is not unresolved library metadata for `com.mchange`; it is an unsupported or unsuitable native Swing/X11 execution path for this generated test.\\n\\n## Intervention applied\\n\\nRemoved the generated test file:\\n\\n- `tests/src/com.mchange/mchange-commons-java/0.2.15/src/test/java/com_mchange/mchange_commons_java/PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest.java`\\n\\nNo metadata files were modified.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe rest of the generated suite still exercises real, non-GUI library behaviors and passed after removing only this Swing/X11-specific test. Preserving the remaining generated tests and support keeps coverage for the metadata-relevant code paths that do work in native image, while dropping only the platform-dependent GUI scenario that is not a reliable metadata signal for this library.\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nAfter removing `PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest.java`, the coordinate passed with:\\n\\n- `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=com.mchange:mchange-commons-java:0.2.15 --stacktrace`\"\n2085:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n2129:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: com.mchange:mchange-commons-java:0.2.15\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe generated support failed only in the native test run, and the failures came from the generated Swing-based test `PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest`, not from unresolved `com.mchange` library metadata.\\n\\nBoth failing test methods instantiate `com.mchange.v2.beans.swing.PropertyBoundTextField`. In the native image run, that triggers JDK AWT/Swing native initialization and fails inside `java.awt.Component.initIDs()` with `java.lang.NoSuchFieldError: java.awt.Component.isPacked`. The second failure is then just a follow-on `NoClassDefFoundError` because `PropertyBoundTextField` could not finish class initialization.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### `propertyBoundTextFieldSyncsInitialAndUpdatedBeanValue()`\\n\\n- Failure: `java.lang.NoSuchFieldError: java.awt.Component.isPacked`\\n- Root cause: non-metadata-related native-image desktop/JNI initialization issue in JDK AWT/Swing.\\n- Why this is not library metadata: the failure occurs in `java.desktop` while initializing `java.awt.Component`, before any missing `com.mchange` reachability entry is reported. This is a JDK desktop support problem, not missing library metadata for `mchange-commons-java`.\\n\\n### `propertyBoundTextFieldAppliesUserChangesBackToBean()`\\n\\n- Failure: `java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: Could not initialize class com.mchange.v2.beans.swing.PropertyBoundTextField`\\n- Root cause: same underlying AWT/Swing initialization failure as above.\\n- Why this is not library metadata: this is only the cascading error after the first test already failed class initialization.\\n\\n## Intervention\\n\\nRemoved the generated test file:\\n\\n- `tests/src/com.mchange/mchange-commons-java/0.2.15/src/test/java/com_mchange/mchange_commons_java/PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest.java`\\n\\nNo metadata files were modified.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe rest of the generated coverage is still valuable and passed after removing the Swing-only test. It continues to validate native-image behavior for the library's reflection, proxies, serialization, naming, logging, thread-pool, collection, JDBC, XML, and codegen utilities.\\n\\nRemoving the single Swing/AWT-native test avoids chasing JDK desktop internals in library metadata while preserving the broader generated support that does exercise `mchange-commons-java` functionality successfully.\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nAfter removing `PropertyComponentBindingUtilityTest.java`, the targeted run succeeded:\\n\\n- `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=com.mchange:mchange-commons-java:0.2.15 --stacktrace`\"\n2151:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n2175:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2235:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2300:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2363:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2388:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2442:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2507:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2572:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2637:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2702:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2765:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2790:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2855:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2909:    \"status\": \"success\",\n2963:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3028:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3093:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3147:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3201:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3255:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3315:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3369:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3429:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3483:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3543:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3597:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3651:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3711:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3771:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3825:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3879:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3933:    \"status\": \"success\",\n3987:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4041:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4106:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4160:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4225:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4259:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4293:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4347:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4401:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4466:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4531:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4596:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4661:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n4705:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: javax.activation:javax.activation-api:1.2.0\\nStage: metadata_fix_failed\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n`nativeTest` failed for a single generated test: `SecuritySupport2Test#getContentTypeLoadsDefaultMimeTypesFromClasspathResource()`.\\n\\nThe failing assertion expected `text/x-securitysupport2` from a generated `META-INF/mimetypes.default` resource, but Native Image returned `application/octet-stream`.\\n\\n## Failure analysis\\n\\nThis remaining failure is **not metadata-related**.\\n\\nEvidence from the Gradle failure output and the Codex metadata-fix log:\\n\\n- The final failing run did **not** report any `Missing*RegistrationError`.\\n- `SecuritySupport4Test` passed in the same native run, which shows `javax.activation.SecuritySupport#getSystemResources(\\\"META-INF/mimetypes.default\\\")` could still find classpath resources in the image.\\n- Codex had already tried resource-related support for `META-INF/mimetypes.default`, so the remaining problem was not an unresolved missing resource registration.\\n\\nRoot cause:\\n\\n- `SecuritySupport2Test` depends on a generated test resource overriding the library's built-in `META-INF/mimetypes.default` so that `MimetypesFileTypeMap` resolves `sample.securitysupport2` to `text/x-securitysupport2`.\\n- The implementation dependency `com.sun.activation:javax.activation:1.2.0` already ships its own `META-INF/mimetypes.default`.\\n- In Native Image, the generated override was not the resource actually consumed by `MimetypesFileTypeMap`, so the lookup fell back to the default mapping and returned `application/octet-stream`.\\n- That is a duplicate-resource / resource-selection behavior issue in this test scenario, not missing reachability metadata for the library API.\\n\\n## Action taken\\n\\nRemoved the non-metadata failing generated test and its test-only support:\\n\\n- deleted `tests/src/javax.activation/javax.activation-api/1.2.0/src/test/java/javax_activation/javax_activation_api/SecuritySupport2Test.java`\\n- deleted `tests/src/javax.activation/javax.activation-api/1.2.0/src/test/resources/META-INF/mimetypes.default`\\n- removed the extra test-jar packaging block from `tests/src/javax.activation/javax.activation-api/1.2.0/build.gradle`\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support still covers meaningful native-image behaviors for this library and should stay in place:\\n\\n- `CommandInfoBeansTest` exercises `CommandInfo` instantiation through the Beans API.\\n- `MailcapCommandMapTest` exercises dynamic handler loading and fallback class loading paths.\\n- `SecuritySupport4Test` still validates resource enumeration through `SecuritySupport#getSystemResources`.\\n\\nThose tests represent real library behavior and were successful in the native run, so the remaining generated support is still useful and should be preserved.\"\n4731:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4796:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4861:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4915:    \"status\": \"success\",\n4969:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5023:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5077:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5135:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5160:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5199:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5233:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5267:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5301:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5335:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5389:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5443:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5503:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n5528:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5593:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n5637:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: jline:jline:2.14.6\\nStage: metadata_fix_failed\\n\\n## Summary\\nThe post-generation failure was caused by a single generated native test, `TerminalLineSettingsTest.constructorUsesInheritedInputWhenAConsoleProviderIsAvailable()`. This was **not** a reachability-metadata failure.\\n\\nThe failing assertion was `assertThat(System.console()).isNotNull()`. In the native-image test process, `System.console()` remained `null`, so the test failed before any missing-registration error occurred.\\n\\n## Root cause\\nThis failure was caused by a runtime/environment assumption in the generated test, not by missing metadata:\\n\\n- The test assumes the native test executable has an inherited interactive console available.\\n- The Gradle failure excerpt shows a plain assertion failure, not a `MissingReflectionRegistrationError`, `MissingResourceRegistrationError`, or any other metadata-related error.\\n- The Codex log shows follow-up attempts to force console-provider access through internal JDK console classes and extra `--add-exports` / `--add-opens` settings. That confirms the problem was tied to console-provider/runtime behavior in native image, not unresolved reachability metadata.\\n\\nBecause this is a non-metadata failure, the correct intervention was to remove the generated test instead of preserving it and asking for more metadata.\\n\\n## Changes made\\nRemoved the generated test and its test-only scaffolding:\\n\\n- `tests/src/jline/jline/2.14.6/src/test/java/org/graalvm/jline/TerminalLineSettingsTest.java`\\n- `tests/src/jline/jline/2.14.6/src/test/resources/junit-platform.properties`\\n- test-only console access flags that had been added to `tests/src/jline/jline/2.14.6/build.gradle`\\n\\nNo metadata files were modified.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\nThe rest of the generated support is still valid and useful:\\n\\n- the remaining generated native tests pass for `jline:jline:2.14.6`\\n- the preserved tests still exercise real library behavior around resource loading, signal handling, reflective terminal loading, HawtJNI native library loading, and OSv terminal integration\\n- the current generated metadata support is still needed for those passing scenarios and should not be discarded just because the console-dependent test made an invalid runtime assumption\\n\\n## Verification\\nAfter removing the console-dependent test, the library passed again with:\\n\\n- `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=jline:jline:2.14.6`\"\n5642:      \"output_tokens_used\": 62277,\n5663:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5713:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n5737:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5791:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5835:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: net.java.dev.jna:jna-platform:5.8.0\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe remaining native-image failures were a mix of:\\n- two earlier metadata-related `OaIdlUtilTest` failures recorded in the Codex log, which Codex addressed by adding the missing `SAFEARRAYBOUND(com.sun.jna.Pointer)` reflection support, and\\n- three non-metadata failures from the final Gradle run, all caused by unsupported native-image/runtime behavior rather than missing metadata.\\n\\nBecause the final failing tests were not metadata issues, I removed the generated tests that caused them:\\n- `tests/src/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.8.0/src/test/java/net_java_dev_jna/jna_platform/ConvertTest.java`\\n- `tests/src/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.8.0/src/test/java/net_java_dev_jna/jna_platform/WindowUtilsMacWindowUtils1Test.java`\\n\\nAfter removing those generated tests, `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=net.java.dev.jna:jna-platform:5.8.0 --stacktrace` passed.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### 1. `ConvertTest.toVariantUsesMatchingVariantConstructorForCompatibleReferenceTypes()`\\n\\n**Classification:** not metadata-related\\n\\n**Why it failed:** native image failed while JNA initialized `com.sun.jna.platform.win32.Variant$VARIANT` and its nested Win32 structure/union types. The failure chain ends in constructor-instantiation problems such as:\\n- `com.sun.jna.platform.win32.OaIdl$CURRENCY$_CURRENCY.<init>()`\\n- `com.sun.jna.platform.win32.WinDef$BYTE.<init>()`\\n\\nThese are JNA/native-image structure-instantiation limitations for nested Win32 wrapper types, not missing reachability metadata. The error is an `IllegalArgumentException`/`NoSuchMethodException` during JNA structure validation, not a `Missing*RegistrationError`.\\n\\n**Action:** removed `ConvertTest.java`.\\n\\n### 2. `ConvertTest.toJavaObjectRestoresComEnumsViaTheirValuesMethod()`\\n\\n**Classification:** not metadata-related\\n\\n**Why it failed:** this test failed only because `Variant.VARIANT` had already failed to initialize for the same reason as the previous test. The reported `NoClassDefFoundError` is a consequence of the earlier JNA `VARIANT` initialization failure, not missing metadata.\\n\\n**Action:** removed `ConvertTest.java`.\\n\\n### 3. `WindowUtilsMacWindowUtils1Test.macWindowAlphaRunnableUsesWindowPeerAlphaSetter()`\\n\\n**Classification:** not metadata-related\\n\\n**Why it failed:** the test forces initialization of AWT `Window`/`Component` machinery while exercising `WindowUtils$MacWindowUtils` in a Linux native-image run. The failure comes from unsupported AWT/JNI platform internals (`java.awt.event.KeyEvent.isProxyActive` / `KeyEvent` initialization mismatch), which is a platform/runtime limitation rather than missing metadata.\\n\\nThis is also a macOS-specific behavior test being executed in a Linux native-image environment.\\n\\n**Action:** removed `WindowUtilsMacWindowUtils1Test.java`.\\n\\n## Metadata-related failures preserved\\n\\nThe Codex log also showed two earlier native-image failures in:\\n- `OaIdlUtilTest.toPrimitiveArrayCreatesNestedJavaArraysFromSafeArrayDimensions()`\\n- `OaIdlUtilTest.toPrimitiveArrayDestroysTheSafeArrayWhenRequested()`\\n\\nThose were metadata-related because they raised a `MissingReflectionRegistrationError` for:\\n\\n- `com.sun.jna.platform.win32.OaIdl$SAFEARRAYBOUND`\\n- constructor `public com.sun.jna.platform.win32.OaIdl$SAFEARRAYBOUND(com.sun.jna.Pointer)`\\n\\nCodex identified and added that missing metadata, so those tests were preserved and now pass. No further metadata changes were made in this intervention.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support still provides useful coverage for `jna-platform:5.8.0`:\\n- Win32 exception handling\\n- DDE helper behavior\\n- file monitoring\\n- enum conversion helpers\\n- `OaIdlUtil` SAFEARRAY handling\\n- TLB template/resource loading\\n- X11 window utility behavior\\n\\nThose areas now pass in native image and validate real library behavior that is still relevant for this coordinate. The removed tests were narrow cases blocked by native-image/JNA/AWT platform limitations, not evidence that the rest of the generated support is invalid.\"\n5861:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5915:    \"status\": \"success\",\n5969:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6023:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6083:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6148:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6213:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6278:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6338:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n6377:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.11\\nStage: metadata_fix_failed\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe generated support failed in native test execution because `EventListenerSupportTest.serializationRoundTripDropsNonSerializableListenersAndRecreatesTransientFields()` hit a GraalVM native-image serialization/reflection limitation during `ObjectInputStream` deserialization.\\n\\n## Failure analysis\\n\\n### Failing test\\n\\n- `tests/src/org.apache.commons/commons-lang3/3.11/src/test/java/org_apache_commons/commons_lang3/EventListenerSupportTest.java`\\n\\n### Root cause\\n\\nThis failure is **not a normal metadata gap** in the generated library support.\\n\\nThe Gradle failure shows `MissingReflectionRegistrationError` for `java.lang.Object.<init>()` from:\\n\\n- `java.io.ObjectStreamClass.newInstance(...)`\\n- `java.io.ObjectInputStream.readOrdinaryObject(...)`\\n\\nThe Codex metadata-fix log shows that it already tried the obvious metadata-based remedies:\\n\\n- adding reflection metadata for `java.lang.Object` default construction,\\n- marking the serialized test class for unsafe allocation,\\n- adding equivalent test-local metadata under `src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image`.\\n\\nDespite that, the runtime still failed with the exact same `java.lang.Object()` error. That means this test is exercising a native-image/JDK deserialization path that is not resolved by the suggested metadata entry, rather than exposing unfinished commons-lang3 metadata.\\n\\n## Intervention\\n\\nRemoved the unsupported generated test:\\n\\n- `tests/src/org.apache.commons/commons-lang3/3.11/src/test/java/org_apache_commons/commons_lang3/EventListenerSupportTest.java`\\n\\nNo metadata files were modified as part of this intervention.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe failure was isolated to one serialization round-trip scenario. The native test report shows the rest of the generated commons-lang3 support working: 52 other tests passed, including coverage for reflection-heavy APIs such as:\\n\\n- `AnnotationUtils`\\n- `ClassUtils`\\n- `ConstructorUtils`\\n- `EqualsBuilder`\\n- `FieldUtils`\\n- `HashCodeBuilder`\\n- `MethodUtils`\\n- `ReflectionToStringBuilder`\\n- `SerializationUtils`\\n- `TypeUtils`\\n\\nThat passing coverage indicates the generated metadata and tests still provide meaningful support for `org.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.11`. Only the `EventListenerSupport` serialization test should be dropped because it depends on a native-image deserialization behavior that Codex could not fix through metadata registration.\"\n6403:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6468:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6518:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6542:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6602:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6667:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n6711:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.apache.ivy:ivy:2.5.2\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe native test run failed in three places after Codex's metadata-fix attempt:\\n\\n- `IvyAuthenticatorTest` failed for a non-metadata reason and was removed.\\n- `IvySettingsTest.initializesBundledResourcesAndDefaultMatchers()` is still failing for missing native-image support around Ivy's bundled settings resources and dynamically loaded default implementation classes.\\n- `MainTest.launchesConfiguredMainClassWithResolvedArguments()` is still failing because Ivy's default settings load bundled XML resources that are not all present in the native image.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### 1. `IvyAuthenticatorTest.installsWithModernAndLegacyAuthenticatorDiscovery()`\\n\\n**Classification:** not metadata-related\\n\\n**Root cause:** this test depends on Ivy reaching into private JDK `java.net.Authenticator` internals (`theAuthenticator` on the legacy path and reflective `getDefault()` access on the modern path). That is a JDK/native-image encapsulation issue around private platform internals, not missing Ivy library metadata.\\n\\nThe Gradle failure here was the null authentication result, not a missing metadata registration error from Ivy itself. The Codex log also shows it tried to paper over this with test-only reflection support for `java.net.Authenticator`, which confirms the failure was about test access to JDK internals rather than missing reachability metadata for the library.\\n\\n**Intervention:** removed `tests/src/org.apache.ivy/ivy/2.5.2/src/test/java/org_apache_ivy/ivy/IvyAuthenticatorTest.java` and removed the related `java.net.Authenticator` entry from `tests/src/org.apache.ivy/ivy/2.5.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/ivy-tests-only/reflect-config.json`.\\n\\n### 2. `IvySettingsTest.initializesBundledResourcesAndDefaultMatchers()`\\n\\n**Classification:** metadata-related\\n\\n**Root cause:** Ivy initializes its default settings by loading bundled XML/properties resources and then resolving many implementation classes by string name through `IvySettings.typeDef(...)`. In the failing native image, those resources/classes were not fully available.\\n\\nThe failure output shows both symptoms:\\n\\n- bundled settings resources are expected from `resource:/org/apache/ivy/core/settings/...`\\n- many default implementation classes cannot be loaded, for example:\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.matcher.GlobPatternMatcher`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.latest.LatestLexicographicStrategy`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.latest.LatestRevisionStrategy`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.latest.LatestTimeStrategy`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.version.ExactVersionMatcher`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.version.PatternVersionMatcher`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.version.SubVersionMatcher`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.version.ChainVersionMatcher`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.resolver.FileSystemResolver`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.resolver.URLResolver`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.plugins.resolver.IBiblioResolver`\\n  - `org.apache.ivy.core.cache.DefaultRepositoryCacheManager`\\n  - and other default resolver/conflict/OSGi classes listed in the Gradle output\\n\\nBecause the default matcher registration depends on those string-driven lookups, `settings.getMatcher(PatternMatcher.GLOB)` ends up `null`.\\n\\n**Why Codex could not resolve it cleanly:** the metadata-fix workflow is tuned for explicit `Missing*RegistrationError` reports. Here Ivy is loading classes and resources indirectly from bundled config files, so native-image reported generic \\\"class not found\\\" and missing-resource failures instead of precise registration suggestions. That left Codex without a narrow, trustworthy metadata delta to apply automatically.\\n\\n### 3. `MainTest.launchesConfiguredMainClassWithResolvedArguments()`\\n\\n**Classification:** metadata-related for the reported failure\\n\\n**Root cause:** Ivy's default startup path loads `resource:/org/apache/ivy/core/settings/ivysettings.xml`, which in turn includes other bundled settings files. The reported failure is the missing bundled resource:\\n\\n- `org/apache/ivy/core/settings/ivysettings-public.xml`\\n\\nThe same settings-loading path is tied to the broader missing bundled-settings support seen in `IvySettingsTest`. The Codex log also shows it diagnosed a resource gap first and then ran into additional string-based Ivy type loading from the same default settings flow.\\n\\n**Why Codex could not resolve it cleanly:** this was not a single missing resource. Ivy's default config is layered, and the native run surfaced one missing include (`ivysettings-public.xml`) while the surrounding log shows additional missing default-setting classes. Codex could not finish because the failures came from chained resource includes plus string-based class loading rather than direct metadata error hints.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support is still useful and should stay in place:\\n\\n- `IvySettingsTest` and `MainTest` are exercising real Ivy behavior, not scaffold-only code.\\n- They expose genuine reachability gaps in Ivy's bundled default-settings initialization path.\\n- The other generated tests (`ConfiguratorTest`, `MemoryUtilTest`, `IvyTest`, and the remaining `MainTest`/`IvySettingsTest` coverage) still provide valid signal for future manual metadata completion.\\n- Removing the metadata-related tests would hide real native-image compatibility problems instead of documenting them.\\n\\n## Files changed during this intervention\\n\\n- Removed `tests/src/org.apache.ivy/ivy/2.5.2/src/test/java/org_apache_ivy/ivy/IvyAuthenticatorTest.java`\\n- Updated `tests/src/org.apache.ivy/ivy/2.5.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/ivy-tests-only/reflect-config.json` to drop the now-unused `java.net.Authenticator` test-only reflection entry\"\n6737:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6797:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6862:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6922:    \"status\": \"success\",\n6976:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7024:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7089:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7154:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7219:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7273:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7333:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7393:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7453:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n7477:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7537:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7576:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7615:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7654:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7708:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7762:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7816:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7870:    \"status\": \"success\",\n7904:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n7948:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.codehaus.woodstox:stax2-api:4.2.2\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nBoth failing native tests had the same root cause: this was a metadata-related failure, not a bad test and not a native-image platform limitation. `XMLValidationSchemaFactory.newInstance(...)` looks up a custom service definition resource at `META-INF/services/org.codehaus.stax2.validation.XMLValidationSchemaFactory.dtd`. In the failing native image, that resource was not registered, so runtime lookup returned no provider and both tests failed with `FactoryConfigurationError`.\\n\\n## Failure breakdown\\n\\n### `loadsFactoryFromSystemResourcesWhenNoClassLoaderIsProvided()`\\n- **Root cause:** missing native-image resource metadata for `META-INF/services/org.codehaus.stax2.validation.XMLValidationSchemaFactory.dtd`\\n- **Why it failed:** the null-classloader path falls back to system resource lookup, but the service file was not embedded in the native image, so no `XMLValidationSchemaFactory` implementation could be found.\\n\\n### `loadsFactoryFromExplicitClassLoaderResources()`\\n- **Root cause:** same missing native-image resource metadata\\n- **Why it failed:** even with the explicit test class loader, the same service file was absent from the native image, so provider discovery failed in the same way.\\n\\n## Codex log findings\\n\\nThe Codex log shows this was already identified correctly as a metadata gap. Codex added a resource entry for:\\n\\n- `META-INF/services/org.codehaus.stax2.validation.XMLValidationSchemaFactory.dtd`\\n\\nwith condition:\\n\\n- `org.codehaus.stax2.validation.XMLValidationSchemaFactory`\\n\\nAfter that change, Codex reran `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.codehaus.woodstox:stax2-api:4.2.2 --stacktrace` and both native tests passed.\\n\\n## Remaining missing metadata\\n\\nNone. The log indicates the metadata issue was resolved by registering the service resource. There is no evidence of a remaining reflection or JNI gap behind this failure.\\n\\n## Intervention decision\\n\\n- **Did not remove any generated tests.**\\n- **Did not modify metadata files in this intervention.**\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe generated support is still valuable because it covers a real native-image compatibility requirement in `stax2-api`: runtime discovery of `XMLValidationSchemaFactory` implementations through a custom `META-INF/services/...dtd` resource. The generated test and its service file validate both lookup variants exercised by the API:\\n\\n- system-resource lookup when no class loader is provided\\n- explicit class-loader resource lookup\\n\\nRemoving that generated support would discard legitimate coverage for a real metadata requirement that Codex already fixed.\"\n7974:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8039:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8083:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.conscrypt:conscrypt-openjdk-uber:2.0.0\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nCodex fixed real metadata gaps for Conscrypt, but the remaining failures in the Gradle output were all non-metadata native-image/runtime issues. I removed the generated tests that exercised those unsupported paths and kept the generated metadata and the passing tests intact.\\n\\n## What failed\\n\\nThe Codex log shows that the metadata changes already fixed two legitimate metadata-driven failures (`OpenSSLECPrivateKeyTest` and `OpenSSLECPublicKeyTest`). The remaining five failures were:\\n\\n1. `DuckTypedPSKKeyManagerTest.invokesSocketDuckTypedPskMethodsDuringHandshake()`\\n2. `NativeLibraryLoader2Test.definesHelperClassIntoTargetClassLoaderWhenHelperCannotBeLoaded()`\\n3. `NativeLibraryLoaderTest.loadsFromOsxJnilibFallbackResourceWhenPrimaryResourceIsMissing()`\\n4. `NativeLibraryLoaderTest.loadsFromOsxDynlibFallbackResourceWhenMappedLibraryNameEndsWithJniLib()`\\n5. `OpenSSLCipherEVP_AEADTest.throwsAeadBadTagExceptionWhenDecryptingTamperedGcmCiphertext()`\\n\\n## Root cause by failure\\n\\n### 1. `DuckTypedPSKKeyManagerTest.invokesSocketDuckTypedPskMethodsDuringHandshake()`\\n\\nThis failed with `java.net.SocketException: Socket is closed` from `org.conscrypt.NativeSsl.doHandshake(...)` during the live socket handshake path.\\n\\nWhy this is not metadata-related:\\n- there is no `Missing*RegistrationError`\\n- the failure happens inside the socket/file-descriptor handshake path after startup, not during reflection/resource lookup\\n- the engine-based PSK test in the same class passes, so the generated support still covers the PSK duck-typing behavior that is actually working in native-image\\n\\nAction taken:\\n- removed only the socket-based PSK test method from `DuckTypedPSKKeyManagerTest.java`\\n\\n### 2. `NativeLibraryLoader2Test.definesHelperClassIntoTargetClassLoaderWhenHelperCannotBeLoaded()`\\n\\nThis failed with `UnsupportedFeatureError: Classes cannot be defined at runtime by default when using ahead-of-time Native Image compilation` while Conscrypt tried to define `org.conscrypt.NativeLibraryUtil` into another class loader.\\n\\nWhy this is not metadata-related:\\n- runtime class definition is a native-image capability limitation, not a reachability metadata gap\\n- the error explicitly points to runtime class loading / predefined classes support, not reflection/resource metadata\\n\\nAction taken:\\n- removed `NativeLibraryLoader2Test.java`\\n\\n### 3. `NativeLibraryLoaderTest.loadsFromOsxJnilibFallbackResourceWhenPrimaryResourceIsMissing()`\\n### 4. `NativeLibraryLoaderTest.loadsFromOsxDynlibFallbackResourceWhenMappedLibraryNameEndsWithJniLib()`\\n\\nBoth tests failed with `expected: 1 but was: 0` because the macOS fallback resource lookup path was never entered in the native executable.\\n\\nWhy this is not metadata-related:\\n- the assertions fail because the code path was not taken at all, not because a resource was missing from metadata\\n- these tests simulate macOS behavior by mutating `os.name`, but native-image preserves the host platform behavior from image build/runtime initialization, so the Linux-built native test binary does not exercise the macOS fallback branch as expected\\n- the remaining `NativeLibraryLoaderTest` still validates the helper-class resource path that does work in native-image\\n\\nAction taken:\\n- removed the two macOS fallback test methods\\n- simplified `NativeLibraryLoaderTest.java` to keep only the passing helper-class coverage\\n\\n### 5. `OpenSSLCipherEVP_AEADTest.throwsAeadBadTagExceptionWhenDecryptingTamperedGcmCiphertext()`\\n\\nThis failed with `SecurityException: Attempted to verify a provider that was not registered at build time: org.conscrypt.OpenSSLProvider`.\\n\\nWhy this is not metadata-related:\\n- this is a native-image security-provider registration/verification issue, not a missing reachability entry in `reachability-metadata.json`\\n- the failure comes from JCE provider verification rules during native execution, not from missing reflection/resource serialization metadata\\n\\nAction taken:\\n- removed `OpenSSLCipherEVP_AEADTest.java`\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should still be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support is still valuable and should stay because Codex did fix real metadata problems:\\n- the Codex log reports that the generated metadata resolved the failures in `OpenSSLECPrivateKeyTest` and `OpenSSLECPublicKeyTest`\\n- after removing only the non-metadata tests above, the library-scoped run succeeds with the rest of the generated support still in place\\n- the surviving test suite continues to validate meaningful Conscrypt behavior in native-image, including TLS engine handshakes, provider integration, platform/socket wrapping, trust-manager reflective access, native library loading helper behavior, and EC key serialization/deserialization\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nVerified with:\\n\\n```bash\\n./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.conscrypt:conscrypt-openjdk-uber:2.0.0 --stacktrace\\n```\\n\\nResult: build successful, `13` native tests passed, `0` failed.\"\n8109:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8163:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8223:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8277:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8331:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8396:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8461:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8520:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8580:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8640:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8696:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n8720:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8780:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n8824:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.immutables:value:2.8.2\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nCodex resolved earlier missing-metadata issues for `org.immutables:value:2.8.2`, but the final `nativeTest` run still had two failing generated tests. Both remaining failures were non-metadata-related native runtime limitations, so I removed the generated test coverage that caused those failures and left metadata files unchanged.\\n\\n## Failure analysis\\n\\n### 1. `org.eclipse.immutables.processor.ProxyProcessor$ProxyClassLoaderTest#delegatesOrgEclipseClassLoadingToTheContextClassLoader()`\\n\\n- **Observed failure:** expected class loader `org.immutables.processor.ProxyProcessor$ProxyClassLoader`, but native execution returned `jdk.internal.loader.ClassLoaders$AppClassLoader`.\\n- **Root cause:** this is a native-image class loading behavior mismatch, not a missing metadata problem. Codex had already fixed the earlier reflective access issue for `ProxyProcessor.delegate`; after that fix, the test still failed because the native executable does not preserve the same custom `URLClassLoader` / delegation behavior that the JVM test expects.\\n- **Action taken:** removed only the failing test method from `tests/src/org.immutables/value/2.8.2/src/test/java/org/eclipse/immutables/processor/ProxyProcessor$ProxyClassLoaderTest.java` and kept the other passing `ProxyProcessor` loading test in the same file.\\n\\n### 2. `org.immutables.value.internal.$generator$.$AnnotationMirrors$GetTypeAnnotationsTest#compilesTypeUseAnnotatedImmutableSource(Path)`\\n\\n- **Observed failure:** `java.lang.ExceptionInInitializerError` from `com.sun.tools.javac.file.Locations`, caused by a `NullPointerException` in `sun.nio.fs.UnixFileSystem.getPath(...)` during `compiler.getStandardFileManager(...)`.\\n- **Root cause:** this is a `javac`-inside-native-image startup failure, not a missing reachability metadata issue. The failure happens during JDK compiler initialization before the generated compilation task can run, and the Codex log shows the metadata-related errors had already been addressed. This is consistent with an unsupported or unstable native-image interaction with `jdk.compiler` file-system initialization rather than missing reflection/resource entries.\\n- **Action taken:** removed `tests/src/org.immutables/value/2.8.2/src/test/java/org/immutables/value/internal/$generator$/$AnnotationMirrors$GetTypeAnnotationsTest.java`.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe rest of the generated support is still valuable and should remain in place:\\n\\n- the remaining generated tests continue to pass in both JVM and native execution for meaningful `org.immutables` behaviors;\\n- the surviving suite still exercises `ProxyProcessor` loading, Guava-derived serialization paths, reflective field access, and suppressed-exception handling;\\n- Codex already added substantial metadata that enabled the passing native coverage, and these final two failures were caused by native runtime behavior rather than missing metadata.\\n\\n## Validation\\n\\nAfter removing the non-metadata-related failing tests, the targeted verification passed:\\n\\n```bash\\n./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.immutables:value:2.8.2 --stacktrace\\n```\"\n8850:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8915:    \"status\": \"success\",\n8975:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9035:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9074:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.jboss.classfilewriter:jboss-classfilewriter:1.2.4.Final\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe post-generation failure was caused by two non-metadata native-image limitations in generated tests, not by additional missing reachability metadata.\\n\\nThe Codex metadata-fix log shows that Codex already added reflection metadata for the exercised `org.jboss.classfilewriter` paths, and that this was enough to make the metadata-driven coverage tests pass. The remaining failures came from tests that attempt runtime class definition or depend on JDK internals that are not available on this GraalVM/JDK 25 setup.\\n\\nI removed the generated failing tests:\\n\\n- `tests/src/org.jboss.classfilewriter/jboss-classfilewriter/1.2.4.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_classfilewriter/jboss_classfilewriter/AnnotationBuilderTest.java`\\n- `tests/src/org.jboss.classfilewriter/jboss-classfilewriter/1.2.4.Final/src/test/java/org_jboss_classfilewriter/jboss_classfilewriter/DefaultClassFactoryTest.java`\\n\\nAfter removing those non-metadata tests, `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.jboss.classfilewriter:jboss-classfilewriter:1.2.4.Final --stacktrace` passed.\\n\\n## Failure-by-failure root cause\\n\\n### 1. `AnnotationBuilderTest.copiesRuntimeVisibleAnnotationsFromJavaAnnotationInstances()`\\n\\nRoot cause: non-metadata native-image limitation.\\n\\nThis test generates bytecode and then calls a custom class loader method that ultimately invokes `ClassLoader#defineClass(...)` at runtime for `GeneratedAnnotationBuilderCoverage...`.\\n\\nThe native run failed with `com.oracle.svm.core.jdk.UnsupportedFeatureError: Classes cannot be defined at runtime by default when using ahead-of-time Native Image compilation`.\\n\\nThat is not a missing-registration error and not a missing metadata problem. The failure is caused by runtime class definition being unsupported by default in Native Image.\\n\\nAction taken: removed the generated test file `AnnotationBuilderTest.java`.\\n\\n### 2. `DefaultClassFactoryTest.invokesMethodInvokeLineUsingSyntheticDefaultClassFactoryWithoutProtectionDomain()`\\n\\nRoot cause: non-metadata JDK/platform incompatibility.\\n\\nThis test initializes `org.jboss.classfilewriter.DefaultClassFactory`, whose implementation reflectively looks up the internal field `AccessibleObject.override`. On this GraalVM/JDK 25 environment, that field is not present, so initialization fails with a synthesized `NoSuchFieldException: override`.\\n\\nThis is not a reachability metadata issue. Metadata cannot restore a removed or unavailable JDK internal field.\\n\\nAction taken: removed the generated test file `DefaultClassFactoryTest.java`.\\n\\n### 3. `DefaultClassFactoryTest.definesClassThroughDefaultFactoryUsingProvidedClassLoaderAndProtectionDomain()`\\n\\nRoot cause: same non-metadata JDK/platform incompatibility as above.\\n\\nThis test is also blocked by `DefaultClassFactory` initialization against the missing `override` field. The assertion mismatch in the failure excerpt is downstream from that initialization problem and does not indicate missing metadata.\\n\\nAction taken: removed the generated test file `DefaultClassFactoryTest.java`.\\n\\n### 4. `DefaultClassFactoryTest.invokesMethodInvokeLineUsingSyntheticDefaultClassFactoryWithProtectionDomain()`\\n\\nRoot cause: same non-metadata JDK/platform incompatibility as above.\\n\\nBecause `DefaultClassFactory` cannot initialize successfully, the test fails with `NoClassDefFoundError: Could not initialize class org.jboss.classfilewriter.DefaultClassFactory`.\\n\\nAgain, this is not a metadata gap; it is a consequence of the unavailable JDK internal field relied on by the library code path.\\n\\nAction taken: removed the generated test file `DefaultClassFactoryTest.java`.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support is still useful and should be kept because it exercises library behavior that does work under Native Image once the generated metadata is present.\\n\\nThe surviving tests still cover:\\n\\n- class structure and bytecode generation\\n- switch generation and exception-handler bytecode\\n- runtime-visible annotation writing for class, field, method, and parameter targets\\n- generic signatures and checked exceptions\\n- `CodeAttribute` frame merging using loaded concrete collection types\\n\\nThose tests all passed after removing the unrelated native-image/JDK-internal cases, so the generated support is not scaffold-only and should not be discarded just because a few tests targeted unsupported runtime class-definition behavior.\\n\\n## Metadata status\\n\\nNo additional metadata-only failure remained in the provided failure set.\\n\\nThe Codex log indicates the metadata fix progressed far enough to resolve the metadata-driven failures that were actually fixable here. The remaining failing tests were blocked by:\\n\\n- Native Image runtime class-definition restrictions\\n- reliance on the missing JDK internal field `override`\\n\\nBecause those are not metadata issues, the correct intervention was to remove the generated tests that depended on those unsupported behaviors rather than remove the rest of the generated support or attempt further metadata edits.\"\n9100:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9134:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9192:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9217:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n9261:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.jboss.logmanager:jboss-logmanager:1.2.0.GA\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe native image built successfully, and the remaining failures were two native-runtime behavioral assertions rather than missing reachability metadata. There was no `Missing*RegistrationError` in the Gradle failure output. The generated support should therefore be kept, but the two unsupported native-only tests were removed.\\n\\nI also confirmed that the generated test suite passes on the JVM and that `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.jboss.logmanager:jboss-logmanager:1.2.0.GA --stacktrace` passes after removing the two failing native-only tests.\\n\\n## Failure analysis\\n\\n### 1. `org.jboss.logmanager.LogManagerTest > readConfigurationFallsBackToLogManagerClassLoaderWhenContextClassLoaderRejectsConfigurator()`\\n\\n- **Root cause:** not metadata-related.\\n- **Why:** `LogManager.construct(...)` uses `Class.forName(name, true, contextClassLoader)` first and then falls back to the `LogManager` class loader. In the native image, the assertion `rejectingClassLoader.rejectedClassLoadAttempted` stayed `false`, even though the configurator was still instantiated successfully.\\n- **Interpretation:** this test depends on observing a custom `ClassLoader.loadClass(...)` rejection path for an image-contained class. That is a native-image class-loading behavior difference, not missing metadata. If metadata were missing, the failure would have been a registration error or reflective instantiation failure, not a plain `assertThat(...).isTrue()` failure.\\n- **Action taken:** removed that test method and its test-only helpers from `tests/src/org.jboss.logmanager/jboss-logmanager/1.2.0.GA/src/test/java/org/jboss/logmanager/LogManagerTest.java`.\\n\\n### 2. `org.jboss.logmanager.formatters.Formatters12Test > extendedExceptionFormattingUsesClassLoadingFallbacksAndClassResourceLookup()`\\n\\n- **Root cause:** not metadata-related.\\n- **Why:** the native failure was again a boolean assertion (`loadedFromBytes`, `rejectedSystemTargetAttempted`, or `classResourceRequested`) staying `false`, not a missing registration error. This test tries to verify that `%E` formatting forces a custom context class loader to byte-define a target class and then performs `.class` resource lookup through that loader.\\n- **Interpretation:** the formatter output path is preserved, but the test relies on runtime-observable custom class loading and resource lookup behavior that native image does not preserve in the same way for image-contained classes. The native image already built successfully, so this is not evidence of missing metadata.\\n- **Action taken:** removed that test method and the test-only helper loader/classes that existed solely for it from `tests/src/org.jboss.logmanager/jboss-logmanager/1.2.0.GA/src/test/java/org/jboss/logmanager/formatters/Formatters12Test.java`.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support still exercises meaningful `jboss-logmanager` behavior that is relevant to reachability metadata:\\n\\n- context-class-loader-based configurator and locator instantiation still has coverage\\n- bootstrap fallback for exception formatting still has coverage\\n- privileged exception class resource lookup still has coverage\\n- property-based handler/filter/formatter/error-manager configuration still has coverage\\n- serialization-related coverage for the map implementations still has coverage\\n- default configuration lookup and typed array handling still have coverage\\n\\nIn short, only the two tests that depended on native-image-incompatible custom class-loading observability were removed. The rest of the generated suite still validates real library behavior and should be preserved.\"\n9287:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n9331:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.jboss.logmanager:jboss-logmanager:1.2.0.GA\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe post-generation failures had two different causes:\\n\\n1. `ConcurrentReferenceHashMapTest.serializationRoundTripPreservesEntries()` in the Codex metadata-fix log was **metadata-related**.\\n2. `Formatters12Test.extendedExceptionFormattingFallsBackToCallerLoaderWhenTcclRejectsTheStackFrameClass()` in the final Gradle failure was **not metadata-related**; it depended on JVM class-loader fallback behavior that does not hold under Native Image.\\n\\nI removed the generated `Formatters12Test.extendedExceptionFormattingFallsBackToCallerLoaderWhenTcclRejectsTheStackFrameClass()` test and kept the rest of the generated support.\\n\\n## Failure analysis\\n\\n### 1. Codex log failure: metadata-related\\n\\nThe Codex log shows a `MissingReflectionRegistrationError` from:\\n\\n- `ConcurrentReferenceHashMapTest.serializationRoundTripPreservesEntries()`\\n\\nMissing entry reported by Native Image:\\n\\n- `java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock$Sync.readObject(java.io.ObjectInputStream)`\\n\\nThat failure came from Java deserialization of `ConcurrentReferenceHashMap`, so it was a real reachability-metadata gap rather than a bad test. This support should be preserved because it covers an actual native-image requirement for the library's serialization path.\\n\\n### 2. Remaining Gradle failure: not metadata-related\\n\\nThe remaining failing test was:\\n\\n- `Formatters12Test.extendedExceptionFormattingFallsBackToCallerLoaderWhenTcclRejectsTheStackFrameClass()`\\n\\nThis failed on:\\n\\n- `assertThat(rejectingClassLoader.wasRejected()).isTrue()`\\n\\nRoot cause:\\n\\n- The test assumes the formatter will first try to resolve the stack-frame class through the thread context class loader, observe a `ClassNotFoundException`, and only then fall back to the caller loader.\\n- In Native Image, class resolution for already-linked image classes does not preserve that JVM class-loading interaction in the same way. The formatted stack trace is still produced, but the custom rejecting loader is never asked to load the class, so `wasRejected()` stays `false`.\\n- No `Missing*RegistrationError` was reported for this failure, so this was not a metadata problem.\\n\\nThis is therefore a Native Image class-loading/runtime-semantics issue in the generated test, and removing that generated test was the correct intervention.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe rest of the generated support still exercises real library behavior and should remain in place:\\n\\n- serialization coverage for `ConcurrentReferenceHashMap` and `FastCopyHashMap`\\n- resource lookup coverage for `DefaultConfigurationLocator`\\n- formatter/resource coverage in `Formatters12Test`\\n- configuration loading and component instantiation coverage in `LogManagerTest` and `PropertyConfiguratorTest`\\n\\nAfter removing only the non-metadata-related formatter fallback test, the coordinate passed again with:\\n\\n- `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.jboss.logmanager:jboss-logmanager:1.2.0.GA`\\n- `GVM_TCK_NATIVE_IMAGE_MODE=future-defaults-all ./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.jboss.logmanager:jboss-logmanager:1.2.0.GA`\\n\\nSo the generated metadata-backed support is still valuable and should be kept; only the unsupported caller-loader fallback assertion needed to be dropped.\"\n9357:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n9396:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.jboss.narayana.jta:jta:5.12.4.Final\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe native test failures were metadata-related, not caused by an unsupported Narayana feature, a test bug, or a platform limitation that would justify deleting generated tests.\\n\\nThe Codex log shows that the generated support was incomplete during the metadata-fix loop. In particular, the two serialization-focused tests needed test-only serialization metadata, and removing them would have thrown away valid coverage for real native-image requirements.\\n\\n## Failure-by-failure root cause\\n\\n### `JNDIManagerTest.bindTransactionSynchronizationRegistryImplementationUsesConfiguredClass()`\\n\\n- The Gradle failure excerpt showed reflective instantiation of `com.arjuna.ats.jta.common.JTAEnvironmentBean` failing through `BeanPopulator`.\\n- That is a metadata-style failure path: Narayana creates its environment beans reflectively, so native-image needs the constructor path to remain available.\\n- This is **not** evidence of a bad generated test. It exercises normal library behavior used by `JNDIManager`.\\n- In the later Codex/native rerun, this test passed, so it should be preserved.\\n\\n### `XAOnePhaseResourceTest.packAndUnpackSerializableXaResource()`\\n\\n- The remaining Codex log shows this was failing because native-image did not have complete serialization registration for the serialized state used by the test.\\n- Codex added test-only `serialization-config.json` entries for the custom serializable fixtures, but the next rerun still failed because Narayana also serialized a `java.lang.String` field inside that object graph.\\n- Root cause: **incomplete test-only serialization metadata**, not an unsupported native-image behavior.\\n- This test should be preserved because it validates real serialization behavior inside `XAOnePhaseResource.pack/unpack`.\\n\\n### `XAResourceRecordTest.saveAndRestoreStateWithSerializableXaResource()`\\n\\n- This failed for the same reason as `XAOnePhaseResourceTest`: the serialized object graph used by `XAResourceRecord.save_state/restore_state` needed complete serialization registration.\\n- The Codex log shows the failure narrowing to missing serialization constructor support, which is metadata-related.\\n- The earlier excerpt also showed reflective/environment initialization issues while entering Narayana state-management code; those are consistent with the same metadata-fix workflow being incomplete rather than a test defect.\\n- This test should be preserved because it covers real native-image-sensitive behavior in `XAResourceRecord` state save/restore.\\n\\n## Why the generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support is valid and should stay because it enables genuine native-image coverage instead of masking a bad test:\\n\\n- `src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/org.jboss.narayana.jta.jta.tests/serialization-config.json` is required for the two serialization-based tests.\\n- Those tests exercise real Narayana code paths that serialize and deserialize XA-related state.\\n- Deleting the tests would reduce coverage of legitimate native-image requirements for this library.\\n\\n## Outcome\\n\\nNo generated tests were removed.\\n\\nAfter preserving the generated test-only serialization support, the focused native lane succeeds:\\n\\n- `./gradlew nativeTest -Pcoordinates=org.jboss.narayana.jta:jta:5.12.4.Final --stacktrace`\\n\\nSo the correct intervention here is to **keep** the generated tests and preserve the generated test-only support rather than delete coverage.\"\n9418:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9442:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9507:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9541:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9575:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9640:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9700:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9754:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9788:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9822:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9882:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9942:    \"status\": \"success\",\n9996:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10054:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10079:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10133:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10172:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10206:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10271:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10332:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10356:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n10395:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.objenesis:objenesis:3.2\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe post-generation failure was caused by three generated native tests that exercise Objenesis serialization-construction paths:\\n\\n- `ObjectInputStreamInstantiatorTest`\\n- `ObjectStreamClassInstantiatorTest`\\n- `SunReflectionFactoryHelperTest#followsSerializationConstructionRulesForSerializableTypes`\\n\\nThese failures are **not** due to missing repository metadata that Codex simply failed to add. Codex already added the suggested test-side reflection registrations for the three `NonSerializableParent` helper constructors, and a clean rebuild still failed with the same `MissingReflectionRegistrationError`s.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### `ObjectInputStreamInstantiatorTest`\\n\\nFailure: native image still rejected reflective invocation of:\\n\\n- `org_objenesis.objenesis.ObjectInputStreamInstantiatorTest$NonSerializableParent()`\\n\\nWhy this is not a metadata gap:\\n\\n- The Codex log shows the exact constructor registration was added to `tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/3.2/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json`.\\n- A clean rebuild showed native-image explicitly applying that test reachability file.\\n- Even with that registration present, runtime still threw the same `MissingReflectionRegistrationError` from the deserialization path inside `ObjectInputStream` / `ObjectStreamClass.newInstance`.\\n\\nConclusion: this is a current native-image limitation/behavior for this serialization-based construction path, not an unfixed metadata omission in this repository.\\n\\n### `ObjectStreamClassInstantiatorTest`\\n\\nFailure: native image still rejected reflective invocation of:\\n\\n- `org_objenesis.objenesis.ObjectStreamClassInstantiatorTest$NonSerializableParent()`\\n\\nWhy this is not a metadata gap:\\n\\n- The exact constructor entry was already present in the generated test reachability metadata.\\n- The failure persisted after a clean native-image rebuild that applied that metadata file.\\n- The exception still came from the JDK serialization allocation path invoked by `ObjectStreamClassInstantiator`.\\n\\nConclusion: same native-image serialization-constructor limitation, not missing library metadata.\\n\\n### `SunReflectionFactoryHelperTest#followsSerializationConstructionRulesForSerializableTypes`\\n\\nFailure: native image still rejected reflective invocation of:\\n\\n- `org_objenesis.objenesis.SunReflectionFactoryHelperTest$NonSerializableParent()`\\n\\nWhy this is not a metadata gap:\\n\\n- Codex had already added the exact constructor registration suggested by the runtime.\\n- The Codex log also shows that a separate `ReflectionFactory` metadata issue was fixed earlier; the remaining failure narrowed down to the serialization constructor invocation itself.\\n- After a clean rebuild, the same constructor-registration error still happened through `SunReflectionFactorySerializationInstantiator`.\\n\\nConclusion: this is also a native-image limitation around serialization-style parent-constructor invocation, not an unresolved metadata entry.\\n\\n## Action taken\\n\\nRemoved the generated failing coverage:\\n\\n- deleted `tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/3.2/src/test/java/org_objenesis/objenesis/ObjectInputStreamInstantiatorTest.java`\\n- deleted `tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/3.2/src/test/java/org_objenesis/objenesis/ObjectStreamClassInstantiatorTest.java`\\n- removed `followsSerializationConstructionRulesForSerializableTypes()` and its serialization-only helper classes from `tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/3.2/src/test/java/org_objenesis/objenesis/SunReflectionFactoryHelperTest.java`\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support still provides meaningful coverage for Objenesis 3.2:\\n\\n- the native test suite still validates the supported constructor-bypass behavior that works in native image\\n- helper and strategy coverage (`ClassUtils`, `ConstructorInstantiator`, `DelegatingToExoticInstantiator`, `SingleInstantiatorStrategy`, `UnsafeFactoryInstantiator`) remains intact\\n- `SunReflectionFactoryHelperTest#createsInstancesWithoutRunningTheTargetConstructor` still validates the non-serialization ReflectionFactory-based path that succeeds in native image\\n- Android/GCJ/PERC tests are assumption-guarded and abort intentionally outside their applicable runtime/platform conditions, so they are not part of the failure\\n\\nAfter removing only the serialization-path tests above, `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.objenesis:objenesis:3.2 --stacktrace` succeeds.\"\n10421:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10486:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10518:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10543:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10603:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10663:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10723:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10757:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10791:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10845:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10879:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10939:    \"status\": \"success\",\n10993:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11058:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n11083:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11148:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n11192:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.20\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe generated Lombok support originally failed in native-image because the test set mixed two kinds of problems:\\n\\n- **recoverable shadow-launch support gaps** that Codex partially fixed for `AgentDynamicAccessTest` and `AnnotationProcessorHiderAnnotationProcessorDynamicAccessTest`, and\\n- **non-metadata native-image/classloading limitations** in the remaining launcher and shadow-loader tests.\\n\\nI removed the non-metadata tests that still failed and kept the generated support that is still valid. After removing those tests, `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.20 --stacktrace` passed.\\n\\n## Root cause by failing test\\n\\n### 1. `AgentDynamicAccessTest`\\n- **Failure from the provided Gradle excerpt:** `NoSuchMethodException` for `lombok.launch.Agent.premain(String, Instrumentation)`.\\n- **Assessment:** metadata/support gap, not a reason to remove the test.\\n- **What happened:** the generated support around Lombok's shadow-launch path was initially incomplete, so the reflective launch path was not available during the native test.\\n- **Outcome:** Codex's follow-up support changes were sufficient here. The test now passes, so it was preserved.\\n\\n### 2. `AnnotationProcessorHiderAnnotationProcessorDynamicAccessTest`\\n- **Failure from the provided Gradle excerpt:** `ClassNotFoundException` for `lombok.core.AnnotationProcessor`.\\n- **Assessment:** metadata/support gap, not a reason to remove the test.\\n- **What happened:** Lombok's annotation processor wrapper depends on shadow-loaded classes/resources. The initial generation did not provide enough support for that path.\\n- **Outcome:** Codex's follow-up support changes were sufficient here. The test now passes, so it was preserved.\\n\\n### 3. `MainDynamicAccessTest`\\n- **Remaining native failure after Codex follow-up:** `ClassNotFoundException: lombok.bytecode.PoolConstantsApp`.\\n- **Assessment:** **not** a reachability-metadata.json problem.\\n- **Root cause:** this test exercises Lombok's SPI-driven shadow class loading for launcher apps. `lombok.bytecode.PoolConstantsApp` is expected to be discovered and loaded through Lombok's `.SCL.lombok` shadow mechanism, but native-image still does not make that path behave like the regular JVM classpath loader.\\n- **Action:** removed the test.\\n\\n### 4. `PatchFixesHiderUtilDynamicAccessTest`\\n- **Remaining native failure after Codex follow-up:** `ClassNotFoundException: lombok.core.Version` from `PatchFixesHider$Util.shadowLoadClass(...)`.\\n- **Assessment:** **not** a reachability-metadata.json problem.\\n- **Root cause:** this test directly depends on Lombok's shadow loader being able to materialize shadow-only classes from `.SCL.lombok` resources inside native-image. That is a classloading/runtime limitation of this generated scenario, not missing reachability metadata in `metadata/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.20/reachability-metadata.json`.\\n- **Action:** removed the test.\\n\\n### 5. `ShadowClassLoaderDynamicAccessTest`\\n- **Remaining native failure after Codex follow-up:** `ClassNotFoundException: org_projectlombok.lombok.LombokLaunchTestSupport`.\\n- **Assessment:** **not** a reachability-metadata.json problem.\\n- **Root cause:** the test expects JVM-style custom class loader delegation/definition behavior from `lombok.launch.ShadowClassLoader`. In the native executable, that expectation does not hold even for the test support class itself, so this is a native-image/classloader behavior mismatch rather than missing metadata.\\n- **Action:** removed the test.\\n\\n## Removed tests\\n\\n- `tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.20/src/test/java/org_projectlombok/lombok/MainDynamicAccessTest.java`\\n- `tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.20/src/test/java/org_projectlombok/lombok/PatchFixesHiderUtilDynamicAccessTest.java`\\n- `tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.20/src/test/java/org_projectlombok/lombok/ShadowClassLoaderDynamicAccessTest.java`\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe surviving support still validates real Lombok native-image behavior that matters:\\n\\n- `AgentDynamicAccessTest` verifies the agent entry path can delegate through Lombok's launcher path in native-image.\\n- `AnnotationProcessorHiderAnnotationProcessorDynamicAccessTest` verifies the annotation-processor wrapper can still construct and initialize the wrapped processor.\\n- The added shadow-override test support/resources are still useful because they are required by the passing preserved tests.\\n\\nIn other words, the remaining generated support is not scaffold-only; it still exercises meaningful Lombok launch and annotation-processor behavior, and the removed tests were the ones blocked by native-image shadow-classloader limitations rather than missing metadata.\"\n11218:    \"status\": \"success_with_intervention\",\n11262:      \"analysis_markdown\": \"# Post-generation intervention report\\n\\nLibrary: org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.22\\nStage: `metadata_fix_failed`\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nCodex had already fixed the metadata-related failures for `org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.22`. The remaining native test failures were all non-metadata issues, so I removed only the generated tests that exercised those unsupported behaviors.\\n\\nRemoved generated tests:\\n- `tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.22/src/test/java/lombok/launch/AgentTest.java`\\n- `lombok.launch.ShadowClassLoaderTest#loadsResourcesFromShadowAwareParentClasspath`\\n- `lombok.launch.ShadowClassLoaderTest#skipsShadowEntriesWhenOverridesAreConfigured`\\n- `lombok.launch.ShadowClassLoaderTest#reusesAlreadyLoadedClassesAndHandlesConcurrentDuplicateDefinitions`\\n\\n## Root cause of each removed failure\\n\\n### `AgentTest#premainInvokesShadowLoadedAgentLauncher`\\nNon-metadata failure.\\n\\nThe test fails with:\\n- `java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Unknown protocol: resource:/lombok/launch/Agent.class`\\n\\nLombok's agent path goes through `lombok.patcher.ClassRootFinder`, which expects a class location URL that behaves like a normal jar/file URL. Inside the native test image it receives a `resource:/...` URL instead, so the Eclipse patcher path aborts before any metadata lookup is relevant.\\n\\n### `AgentTest#agentmainInvokesShadowLoadedAgentLauncherAndRequestsReload`\\nNon-metadata failure.\\n\\nThis fails for the same reason as `premain`: the agent bootstrap logic depends on URL/protocol handling that is different inside Native Image, and it dies on `resource:/...` before metadata could help.\\n\\n### `ShadowClassLoaderTest#loadsResourcesFromShadowAwareParentClasspath`\\nNon-metadata failure.\\n\\nThe test expects JVM-style discovery of temp-dir parent resources and shadow entries via `ShadowClassLoader#getResources(...)`. In the native executable, those runtime-created parent resources are not enumerated the same way, so the expected resource list is empty. This is a resource-loading/runtime-behavior mismatch, not missing reachability metadata.\\n\\n### `ShadowClassLoaderTest#skipsShadowEntriesWhenOverridesAreConfigured`\\nNon-metadata failure.\\n\\nThis is the same family of issue as the previous test: it depends on JVM resource lookup behavior across runtime-created parent class loaders and override directories. In Native Image the expected shadow resource is not found, so the assertion fails. No missing reflection/resource registration error is involved.\\n\\n### `ShadowClassLoaderTest#reusesAlreadyLoadedClassesAndHandlesConcurrentDuplicateDefinitions`\\nNon-metadata failure.\\n\\nThe test intentionally defines the same predefined class through multiple `ShadowClassLoader` instances. Native Image reports:\\n- `UnsupportedFeatureError: A predefined class can be loaded (defined) at runtime only once by a single class loader.`\\n\\nThat is an explicit Native Image limitation around predefined/runtime-defined classes, not a metadata gap.\\n\\n## Why the remaining generated support should be preserved\\n\\nThe remaining generated support is still useful and should stay in place because the surviving tests continue to validate real Lombok native behavior:\\n- `AnnotationProcessorHiderAnnotationProcessorTest` proves the shadow-loaded annotation processor path works with the generated metadata.\\n- `MainTest` proves `lombok.launch.Main` can still delegate to the shadow-loaded core main class inside Native Image.\\n- `PatchFixesHiderUtilTest` still exercises Lombok's reflective utility path.\\n- `ShadowClassLoaderTest#loadsClassesFromPrependedParents` still covers supported shadow class loading behavior.\\n\\nThe generated test resources under `tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.22/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/` are therefore still needed by the tests that remain.\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\nAfter removing only the non-metadata tests, the coordinate passes:\\n\\n- `./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.22`\"\n11288:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11342:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11396:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11456:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11510:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11544:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11578:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11643:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11697:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11762:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11823:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n11847:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11907:    \"status\": \"success\",\n11967:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12015:    \"library\": \"org.sonatype.aether:aether-util:1.7\",\n12017:    \"ending_commit\": \"d8530666c390257315511823ac03b45f96710342\",\n12021:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12075:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12135:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12200:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12260:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12304:    \"status\": \"failure\",\n12328:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12382:    \"status\": \"success\",\n12436:    \"status\": \"success\",\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
